README.md
     1→# dotenv
     5→Dotenv is a zero-dependency module that loads environment variables from a `.env` file into [`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env). Storing configuration in the environment separate from code is based on [The Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/config) methodology.
     6→
     7→[Watch the tutorial](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtkZR0NFd1g)
     8→
     9→&nbsp;
    10→
    11→## Usage
    13→Install it.
    14→
    15→```sh
    16→npm install dotenv --save
    17→```
    18→
    19→Create a `.env` file in the root of your project:
    20→
    21→```ini
    22→# .env
    23→S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    24→SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    25→```
    26→
    27→And as early as possible in your application, import and configure dotenv:
    28→
    29→```javascript
    30→require('dotenv').config() // or import 'dotenv/config' if you're using ES6
    31→...
    32→console.log(process.env) // remove this after you've confirmed it is working
    33→```
    34→
    35→That's it. `process.env` now has the keys and values you defined in your `.env` file:
    36→
    37→&nbsp;
    38→
    39→## Advanced
    43→Import with [ES6](#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import):
    44→
    45→```javascript
    46→import 'dotenv/config'
    47→```
    48→
    49→ES6 import if you need to set config options:
    50→
    51→```javascript
    52→import dotenv from 'dotenv'
    53→dotenv.config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
    54→```
    55→
    56→</details>
    57→<details><summary>bun</summary><br>
    58→
    59→```sh
    60→bun add dotenv
    61→```
    62→
    63→</details>
    64→<details><summary>yarn</summary><br>
    65→
    66→```sh
    67→yarn add dotenv
    68→```
    69→
    70→</details>
    71→<details><summary>pnpm</summary><br>
    72→
    73→```sh
    74→pnpm add dotenv
    75→```
    76→
    77→</details>
    78→<details><summary>Monorepos</summary><br>
    79→
    80→For monorepos with a structure like `apps/backend/app.js`, put it the `.env` file in the root of the folder where your `app.js` process runs.
    81→
    82→```ini
    83→# app/backend/.env
    84→S3_BUCKET="YOURS3BUCKET"
    85→SECRET_KEY="YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE"
    86→```
    87→
    88→</details>
    89→<details><summary>Multiline Values</summary><br>
    90→
    91→If you need multiline variables, for example private keys, those are now supported (`>= v15.0.0`) with line breaks:
    92→
    93→```ini
    94→PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
    95→...
    96→Kh9NV...
    97→...
    98→-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----"
    99→```
   100→
   101→Alternatively, you can double quote strings and use the `\n` character:
   102→
   103→```ini
   104→PRIVATE_KEY="-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\nKh9NV...\n-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----\n"
   105→```
   106→
   107→</details>
   108→<details><summary>Comments</summary><br>
   109→
   110→Comments may be added to your file on their own line or inline:
   111→
   112→```ini
   113→# This is a comment
   114→SECRET_KEY=YOURSECRETKEYGOESHERE # comment
   115→SECRET_HASH="something-with-a-#-hash"
   116→```
   117→
   118→Comments begin where a `#` exists, so if your value contains a `#` please wrap it in quotes. This is a breaking change from `>= v15.0.0` and on.
   119→
   120→</details>
   121→<details><summary>Parsing</summary><br>
   122→
   123→The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   124→
   125→```javascript
   126→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   127→const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   128→const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   129→console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   130→```
   131→
   132→</details>
   133→<details><summary>Preload</summary><br>
   134→
   135→> Note: Consider using [`dotenvx`](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) instead of preloading. I am now doing (and recommending) so.
   136→>
   137→> It serves the same purpose (you do not need to require and load dotenv), adds better debugging, and works with ANY language, framework, or platform. – [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   138→
   139→You can use the `--require` (`-r`) [command line option](https://nodejs.org/api/cli.html#-r---require-module) to preload dotenv. By doing this, you do not need to require and load dotenv in your application code.
   140→
   141→```bash
   142→$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   143→```
   144→
   145→The configuration options below are supported as command line arguments in the format `dotenv_config_<option>=value`
   146→
   147→```bash
   148→$ node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env dotenv_config_debug=true
   149→```
   150→
   151→Additionally, you can use environment variables to set configuration options. Command line arguments will precede these.
   152→
   153→```bash
   154→$ DOTENV_CONFIG_<OPTION>=value node -r dotenv/config your_script.js
   155→```
   156→
   157→```bash
   158→$ DOTENV_CONFIG_ENCODING=latin1 DOTENV_CONFIG_DEBUG=true node -r dotenv/config your_script.js dotenv_config_path=/custom/path/to/.env
   159→```
   160→
   161→</details>
   162→<details><summary>Variable Expansion</summary><br>
   163→
   164→Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for variable expansion.
   165→
   166→Reference and expand variables already on your machine for use in your .env file.
   167→
   168→```ini
   169→# .env
   170→USERNAME="username"
   171→DATABASE_URL="postgres://${USERNAME}@localhost/my_database"
   172→```
   173→```js
   174→// index.js
   175→console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   176→```
   177→```sh
   178→$ dotenvx run --debug -- node index.js
   179→[dotenvx@0.14.1] injecting env (2) from .env
   180→DATABASE_URL postgres://username@localhost/my_database
   181→```
   182→
   183→</details>
   184→<details><summary>Command Substitution</summary><br>
   185→
   186→Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) for command substitution.
   187→
   188→Add the output of a command to one of your variables in your .env file.
   189→
   190→```ini
   191→# .env
   192→DATABASE_URL="postgres://$(whoami)@localhost/my_database"
   193→```
   194→```js
   195→// index.js
   196→console.log('DATABASE_URL', process.env.DATABASE_URL)
   197→```
   198→```sh
