   319→## Agents
   323→> Software is changing, and dotenv must change with it—that is why I built [agentic secret storage (AS2)](https://dotenvx.com/as2). Agents run code without humans at terminals, so plaintext `.env` files are the wrong primitive.
   324→>
   325→> AS2 is built for autonomous software: encrypted by default, zero console access, and cryptography‑first delivery that keeps operators out of the loop.
   326→>
   327→> It is backed by [Vestauth](https://github.com/vestauth/vestauth), the trusted, pioneering auth layer for agents—giving each agent a cryptographic identity so requests are signed with private keys and verified with public keys. No shared secrets to leak.
   328→>
   329→> It's what I'm using now. - [motdotla](https://mot.la)
   330→
   331→### Quickstart
   333→Install vestauth and initialize your agent.
   334→
   335→```bash
   336→npm i -g vestauth
   337→
   338→vestauth agent init
   339→```
   340→
   341→Your agent `set`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   342→
   343→```bash
   344→vestauth agent curl -X POST https://as2.dotenvx.com/set -d '{"KEY":"value"}'
   345→```
   346→
   347→And your agent `get`s secrets with a simple `curl` endpoint:
   348→
   349→```bash
   350→vestauth agent curl "https://as2.dotenvx.com/get?key=KEY"
   351→```
   352→
   353→That's it! This new primitive unlocks secrets access for agents without human-in-the-loop, oauth flows, or API keys. It's the future for agents.
   354→
   355→&nbsp;
   356→
   357→## FAQ
   361→No.
   362→
   363→Unless you encrypt it with [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx). Then we recommend you do.
   364→
   365→</details>
   366→<details><summary>What about variable expansion?</summary><br/>
   367→
   368→Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx).
   369→
   370→</details>
   371→<details><summary>Should I have multiple `.env` files?</summary><br/>
   372→
   373→We recommend creating one `.env` file per environment. Use `.env` for local/development, `.env.production` for production and so on. This still follows the twelve factor principles as each is attributed individually to its own environment. Avoid custom set ups that work in inheritance somehow (`.env.production` inherits values form `.env` for example). It is better to duplicate values if necessary across each `.env.environment` file.
   374→
   375→> In a twelve-factor app, env vars are granular controls, each fully orthogonal to other env vars. They are never grouped together as “environments”, but instead are independently managed for each deploy. This is a model that scales up smoothly as the app naturally expands into more deploys over its lifetime.
   376→>
   377→> – [The Twelve-Factor App](http://12factor.net/config)
   378→
   379→Additionally, we recommend using [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to encrypt and manage these.
   380→
   381→</details>
   382→
   383→<details><summary>How do I use dotenv with `import`?</summary><br/>
   384→
   385→Simply..
   386→
   387→```javascript
   388→// index.mjs (ESM)
   389→import 'dotenv/config' // see https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv#how-do-i-use-dotenv-with-import
   390→import express from 'express'
   391→```
   392→
   393→A little background..
   394→
   395→> When you run a module containing an `import` declaration, the modules it imports are loaded first, then each module body is executed in a depth-first traversal of the dependency graph, avoiding cycles by skipping anything already executed.
   396→>
   397→> – [ES6 In Depth: Modules](https://hacks.mozilla.org/2015/08/es6-in-depth-modules/)
   398→
   399→What does this mean in plain language? It means you would think the following would work but it won't.
   400→
   401→`errorReporter.mjs`:
   402→```js
   403→class Client {
   404→  constructor (apiKey) {
   405→    console.log('apiKey', apiKey)
   406→
   407→    this.apiKey = apiKey
   408→  }
   409→}
   410→
   411→export default new Client(process.env.API_KEY)
   412→```
   413→`index.mjs`:
   414→```js
   415→// Note: this is INCORRECT and will not work
   416→import * as dotenv from 'dotenv'
   417→dotenv.config()
   418→
   419→import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs' // process.env.API_KEY will be blank!
   420→```
   421→
   422→`process.env.API_KEY` will be blank.
   423→
   424→Instead, `index.mjs` should be written as..
   425→
   426→```js
   427→import 'dotenv/config'
   428→
   429→import errorReporter from './errorReporter.mjs'
   430→```
   431→
   432→Does that make sense? It's a bit unintuitive, but it is how importing of ES6 modules work. Here is a [working example of this pitfall](https://github.com/dotenv-org/examples/tree/master/usage/dotenv-es6-import-pitfall).
   433→
   434→There are two alternatives to this approach:
   435→
   436→1. Preload with dotenvx: `dotenvx run -- node index.js` (_Note: you do not need to `import` dotenv with this approach_)
   437→2. Create a separate file that will execute `config` first as outlined in [this comment on #133](https://github.com/motdotla/dotenv/issues/133#issuecomment-255298822)
   438→</details>
   439→
   440→<details><summary>Can I customize/write plugins for dotenv?</summary><br/>
   441→
   442→Yes! `dotenv.config()` returns an object representing the parsed `.env` file. This gives you everything you need to continue setting values on `process.env`. For example:
   443→
   444→```js
   445→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   446→const variableExpansion = require('dotenv-expand')
   447→const myEnv = dotenv.config()
   448→variableExpansion(myEnv)
   449→```
   450→
   451→</details>
   452→<details><summary>What rules does the parsing engine follow?</summary><br/>
   453→
   454→The parsing engine currently supports the following rules:
   455→
   456→- `BASIC=basic` becomes `{BASIC: 'basic'}`
   457→- empty lines are skipped
   458→- lines beginning with `#` are treated as comments
   459→- `#` marks the beginning of a comment (unless when the value is wrapped in quotes)
   460→- empty values become empty strings (`EMPTY=` becomes `{EMPTY: ''}`)
   461→- inner quotes are maintained (think JSON) (`JSON={"foo": "bar"}` becomes `{JSON:"{\"foo\": \"bar\"}"`)
   462→- whitespace is removed from both ends of unquoted values (see more on [`trim`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/String/Trim)) (`FOO=  some value  ` becomes `{FOO: 'some value'}`)
   463→- single and double quoted values are escaped (`SINGLE_QUOTE='quoted'` becomes `{SINGLE_QUOTE: "quoted"}`)
   464→- single and double quoted values maintain whitespace from both ends (`FOO="  some value  "` becomes `{FOO: '  some value  '}`)
   465→- double quoted values expand new lines (`MULTILINE="new\nline"` becomes
   466→
   467→```
   468→{MULTILINE: 'new
   469→line'}
   470→```
   471→
   472→- backticks are supported (`` BACKTICK_KEY=`This has 'single' and "double" quotes inside of it.` ``)
   473→
   474→</details>
   475→<details><summary>What about syncing and securing .env files?</summary><br/>
   476→
   477→Use [dotenvx](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx) to unlock syncing encrypted .env files over git.
   478→
   479→</details>
   480→<details><summary>What if I accidentally commit my `.env` file to code?</summary><br/>
   481→
   482→Remove it, [remove git history](https://docs.github.com/en/authentication/keeping-your-account-and-data-secure/removing-sensitive-data-from-a-repository) and then install the [git pre-commit hook](https://github.com/dotenvx/dotenvx#pre-commit) to prevent this from ever happening again. 
   483→
   484→```
   485→npm i -g @dotenvx/dotenvx
   486→dotenvx precommit --install
   487→```
   488→
   489→</details>
   490→<details><summary>What happens to environment variables that were already set?</summary><br/>
   491→
   492→By default, we will never modify any environment variables that have already been set. In particular, if there is a variable in your `.env` file which collides with one that already exists in your environment, then that variable will be skipped.
   493→
   494→If instead, you want to override `process.env` use the `override` option.
   495→
   496→```javascript
   497→require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   498→```
   499→
   500→</details>
   501→<details><summary>How can I prevent committing my `.env` file to a Docker build?</summary><br/>
   502→
   503→Use the [docker prebuild hook](https://dotenvx.com/docs/features/prebuild).
   504→
   505→```bash
   506→# Dockerfile
   507→...
   508→RUN curl -fsS https://dotenvx.sh/ | sh
   509→...
   510→RUN dotenvx prebuild
   511→CMD ["dotenvx", "run", "--", "node", "index.js"]
   512→```
   513→
   514→</details>
   515→<details><summary>How come my environment variables are not showing up for React?</summary><br/>
   516→
      →…
   579→## Docs
   581→Dotenv exposes four functions:
   582→
   583→* `config`
   584→* `parse`
   585→* `populate`
   586→
   587→### Config
   589→`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590→[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591→and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   592→
   593→```js
   594→const result = dotenv.config()
   595→
   596→if (result.error) {
   597→  throw result.error
   598→}
   599→
   600→console.log(result.parsed)
   601→```
   602→
   603→You can additionally, pass options to `config`.
   604→
   605→#### Options …
   607→##### path
   609→Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   610→
   611→Specify a custom path if your file containing environment variables is located elsewhere.
   612→
   613→```js
   614→require('dotenv').config({ path: '/custom/path/to/.env' })
   615→```
   616→
   617→By default, `config` will look for a file called .env in the current working directory.
   618→
   619→Pass in multiple files as an array, and they will be parsed in order and combined with `process.env` (or `option.processEnv`, if set). The first value set for a variable will win, unless the `options.override` flag is set, in which case the last value set will win.  If a value already exists in `process.env` and the `options.override` flag is NOT set, no changes will be made to that value. 
   620→
   621→```js  
   622→require('dotenv').config({ path: ['.env.local', '.env'] })
   623→```
   624→
   625→##### quiet
   627→Default: `false`
   628→
   629→Suppress runtime logging message.
   630→
   631→```js
   632→// index.js
   633→require('dotenv').config({ quiet: false }) // change to true to suppress
   634→console.log(`Hello ${process.env.HELLO}`)
   635→```
   636→
   637→```ini
   638→# .env
   639→HELLO=World
   640→```
   641→
   642→```sh
   643→$ node index.js
   644→[dotenv@17.0.0] injecting env (1) from .env
   645→Hello World
   646→```
   647→
   648→##### encoding
   650→Default: `utf8`
   651→
   652→Specify the encoding of your file containing environment variables.
   653→
   654→```js
   655→require('dotenv').config({ encoding: 'latin1' })
   656→```
   657→
   658→##### debug
   660→Default: `false`
   661→
   662→Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   663→
   664→```js
   665→require('dotenv').config({ debug: process.env.DEBUG })
   666→```
   667→
   668→##### override
   670→Default: `false`
   671→
   672→Override any environment variables that have already been set on your machine with values from your .env file(s). If multiple files have been provided in `option.path` the override will also be used as each file is combined with the next. Without `override` being set, the first value wins. With `override` set the last value wins. 
   673→
   674→```js
   675→require('dotenv').config({ override: true })
   676→```
   677→
   678→##### processEnv
   680→Default: `process.env`
   681→
   682→Specify an object to write your environment variables to. Defaults to `process.env` environment variables.
   683→
   684→```js
   685→const myObject = {}
   686→require('dotenv').config({ processEnv: myObject })
   687→
   688→console.log(myObject) // values from .env
   689→console.log(process.env) // this was not changed or written to
   690→```
   691→
   692→### Parse
   694→The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695→variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696→an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   697→
   698→```js
   699→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   700→const buf = Buffer.from('BASIC=basic')
   701→const config = dotenv.parse(buf) // will return an object
   702→console.log(typeof config, config) // object { BASIC : 'basic' }
   703→```
   704→
   705→#### Options …
   707→##### debug
   709→Default: `false`
   710→
   711→Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being set as you expect.
   712→
   713→```js
   714→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   715→const buf = Buffer.from('hello world')
   716→const opt = { debug: true }
   717→const config = dotenv.parse(buf, opt)
   718→// expect a debug message because the buffer is not in KEY=VAL form
   719→```
   720→
   721→### Populate
   723→The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   724→
   725→For example, customizing the source:
   726→
   727→```js
   728→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   729→const parsed = { HELLO: 'world' }
   730→
   731→dotenv.populate(process.env, parsed)
   732→
   733→console.log(process.env.HELLO) // world
   734→```
   735→
   736→For example, customizing the source AND target:
   737→
   738→```js
   739→const dotenv = require('dotenv')
   740→const parsed = { HELLO: 'universe' }
   741→const target = { HELLO: 'world' } // empty object
   742→
   743→dotenv.populate(target, parsed, { override: true, debug: true })
   744→
   745→console.log(target) // { HELLO: 'universe' }
   746→```
   747→
   748→#### options …
   750→##### Debug
   752→Default: `false`
   753→
   754→Turn on logging to help debug why certain keys or values are not being populated as you expect.
   755→
   756→##### override
   758→Default: `false`
   759→
   760→Override any environment variables that have already been set.
   761→
   762→&nbsp;
   763→
   764→## CHANGELOG
   766→See [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   767→
   768→&nbsp;
   769→
   770→## Who's using dotenv?
   772→[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
   773→
   774→Projects that expand it often use the [keyword "dotenv" on npm](https://www.npmjs.com/search?q=keywords:dotenv).

